Yes it can become a great tourist destination if authorities become more open minded and intelligent. On the one hand there are bloggers promoting travel to Pakistan, I dreamed to visit the country after seeing these videos. A lot of effort was put to make the trip happen. Finally a big part of it was ruined by police and agency harassment, Pakistan is safe but in a lot of areas police won't let you go alone (illogical?), and the worst part was extending visa which is total mess and corrupt (was required 100$ for approval after paying online fee). On the one hand tour agents promote tourism to do business, on the other hand authorities create huge obstacles. Two fires and you are stuck between them. Fair to mention rude behaviour of some government officers which is total nonsense in relation to tourists who they want to attract to their country.
Please mention such moments in your stories so people don't get trapped trying to discover Pakistan. Personally I would like to go back to see more of balochistan and north, but will do this trip only when I read that normal traveller had good time with authorities there.

These were the words that Amir Khosrow used to describe Kashmir. He was a poet during the Malik dynasty when he entered Kashmir via the Karakoram. This is an early reference to Kashmir as a paradise. Kashmir continued to be a favorite destination for rulers. The most famous of these was Shah Jahan Aurangzeb who used Srinagar as his summer capital. The Mughals had planted many gardens which added an organized layer to the independent beauty of Kashmir had added. I , as an Indian can definitely say that India is the best place for tourism and these are my arguements:
You want mountains? We have access to the great himalyan range which spreads across the coutry. You want green / snow peaked / rock / high altitude or any other type of mountain, name it we have it.
You want to enjoy forest& wildlife, we have plenty of it be it tropical forest's, tiger reserve's and national parks like sundarban.
You want beaches, the eastern ghat & the western ghat have more than you can ever visit. Not to forget spectacular andaman's & lakhsadweep.
You want history? We definitely have alot more monuments than any other country in the world, including Taj Mahal which is one of the wonders of world. Our entire nation is just full of it.
You want food? UNESCO has called Hyderabad culinary capital of the world, and there are alot of other cities which give strong competition to hyderabad.
You want desert? Welcome to Rajisthan.
You want culture? Here in India the culture and the language changes more frequently than the landscape.
You want to see garden's like apple/ tea / coffee or stuff's like step farming, WEED farming or anything else, Just name it and we have it.
No hate for pakistan, Just wanted to make my point.

Today Bhutan is basically under semi-occupation by India with tens of thousands of Indian troops stationed in the country of some seven hundred thousands. India wants to keep Bhutan isolated and forbids it to have any diplomatic relations with any major countries. Today Bhutan does not have diplomatic relation with the US, UK, France, Russia or even China, its neighbor on the north because India does not allow it. Bhutan is under the constant danger of being annexed by India like its next door neighbor Sikkim, an independent Himalayan Buddhist kingdom even smaller than Bhutan and was invaded and annexed by India in 1975. Nepal is a little bit better because it has more population and is harder for India to digest. Still what India did to Nepal is just as disgusting. Aside from the land grab from Nepal by India in 1962, India also seeks to isolate Nepal. A few years ago Nepal had a devastating earthquake an a few months later India took advantage of the misery of Nepal by enacting an embargo on Nepal to maximize its pain just because the Nepali congress passed a law not to India's liking. This kind of meddling is a major source of resentments among India's neighbors.
Basically today's India's foreign policy orientation towards its neighbors is a continuation of the expansionist British Raj, in other words a lot of bullying and land grabbing. I wish for a Pakistan with better attitude and unity. Pakistan Zindabad
